4.comment: Kurt Warner finished 40-of-57, 472 yards and 2 touchdowns, leading the Cardinals to 35 points. However, he tossed 3 interceptions and fumbled 4 times, completely ruining Arizona's chances of winning. Warner fumbled away the ball in the red zone on the opening drive of the game. Two possessions later, Warner tossed a pick-six. In between, a Cardinals field goal was blocked. That's 3 blown opportunities.    Three Arizona receivers eclipsed the century mark.

14.comment: Kurt Warner finished 24-of-33, 279 yards, 1 touchdown and a pick. Larry Fitzgerald, who had 6 receptions for 73 yards, had Warner's lone score. Steve Breaston caught 7 balls for 90 yards, while Anquan Boldin hauled in 5 passes for 62 yards. Yet another 30-yard performance from Tim Hightower. Hightower has rushed between 20 and 39 yards in 8 of 13 games this year. Fortunately for his fantasy owners, he scored a touchdown. By the way, it should be noted that Arizona clinched the NFC West with this victory, marking the first time they've won their division since 1975. Dan Marino Record Watch: Kurt Warner now has 4,020 passing yards on the season. He's on pace for 4,948 yards. Dan Marino had 5,084 yards in 1984.

15.comment: Kurt Warner interception. The third occurred after a Cardinals fumble.    Still, Tarvaris Jackson's 4 touchdowns look impressive. But I think it's more important that Jackson did what he had to do - refrain from committing turnovers and convert third downs. He was 11-of-17 for 163 yards.    Jackson's 4 scores went to Bobby Wade, Bernard Berrian, Chester Taylor and Sidney Rice. However, no Viking wideout had more than 2 receptions.    Adrian Peterson didn't get into the end zone, but he was still able to compile 165 yards on 28 rushes.    Speaking of rushes, Arizona running backs carried the ball just 7 times, as the Cardinals simply didn't bother challenging the Williams Wall. 21.comment: Kurt Warner set an NFL record for completion percentage in game, going 24-of-26 for 243 yards and 2 scores. Warner looked like he was 50 years old last week, but he seemed rejuvenated on Sunday, though it should be noted that his longest completion was only 22 yards. It's amazing what playing a quitting team can do for you.    Chris Wells ran well in this game - 7 carries for 44 yards - but he fumbled twice and wasn't given the ball much late in the contest.
